The Beck family, three generations strong, set out to harvest disease-free oysters after years of waiting for them to grow to legal size.
Managed reserves and oyster sanctuaries aim to revive the dwindling oyster population in the Chesapeake Bay.
Concerns over introducing Asian oysters linger, with calls for more research before a decision is made.
Cleanup efforts face challenges, with funding issues and slow progress in meeting water standards.
Despite setbacks, the hope remains that oysters will reclaim their role as a vital part of the bay's ecosystem and economy.
